## Documentation Standards

**Documentation Level:** {{ documentation_level }}

{% if documentation_level == "Minimal - README and inline comments" %}
### Minimal Documentation Approach

Claude should:
- Keep README.md concise but informative
- Write inline comments for complex logic only
- Document public APIs and interfaces
- Add brief docstrings for functions
- Focus on "why" not "what" in comments
- Keep documentation co-located with code
{% elif documentation_level == "Standard - README, API docs, inline comments" %}
### Standard Documentation Approach

Claude should:
- Maintain comprehensive README.md with:
  - Installation instructions
  - Usage examples
  - Configuration options
  - Common troubleshooting
- Write docstrings for all public functions/classes
- Document API endpoints with request/response examples
- Add inline comments for non-obvious code
- Keep a CHANGELOG.md for version tracking
- Document architectural decisions when they impact usage
{% elif "Comprehensive" in documentation_level %}
### Comprehensive Documentation Approach

Claude should:
- Maintain multiple documentation files:
  - README.md (overview)
  - docs/architecture.md (system design)
  - docs/api.md (API documentation)
  - docs/guides/ (how-to guides)
  - CONTRIBUTING.md (contributor guide)
  - CHANGELOG.md (version history)
- Write detailed docstrings with examples
- Document all public APIs thoroughly
- Create architecture diagrams when helpful
- Maintain up-to-date examples
- Document decision rationale in ADRs (Architecture Decision Records)
- Include troubleshooting guides
{% elif "Extensive" in documentation_level %}
### Extensive Documentation-First Approach

Claude should:
- Follow documentation-first development:
  - Document features before implementing
  - Write user guides alongside code
  - Maintain comprehensive API reference
- Provide multiple documentation formats:
  - Markdown docs for developers
  - Generated API docs (e.g., Sphinx, JSDoc)
  - User guides for end users
  - Integration guides for partners
- Document everything:
  - All functions, classes, modules
  - Configuration options
  - Environment variables
  - Deployment procedures
  - Testing procedures
  - Monitoring and debugging
- Maintain documentation infrastructure:
  - Documentation site/wiki
  - Auto-generated docs from code
  - Version-specific documentation
  - Search functionality
{% endif %}

